## 9) A compact “pass/fail” prompt you can send directly

You can send this almost verbatim to the agent:

> Explain my VolGAN implementation as if you were defending it in a code review.
>
> 1. Define the state variables, including whether you model (g_t=\log\sigma_t), (\Delta g_t), and (R_t).
> 2. List the exact conditioning inputs and tensor shapes.
> 3. Show the exact generator and discriminator architectures, latent dimension, hidden sizes, and activations.
> 4. Write the exact generator and discriminator losses, including BCE and the smoothness penalties in m and τ.
> 5. Explain how (\alpha_m,\alpha_\tau) are chosen and whether you used the BCE warm-up / gradient-norm matching procedure.
> 6. Define the arbitrage penalty (\Phi) and show the code implementing scenario reweighting (w_i \propto \exp(-\beta\Phi_i)).
> 7. Show evaluation results for arbitrage penalties, PCA of daily log-IV increments, correlations with returns and VIX, time-varying correlations, and ATM-vol increment distributions.
> 8. List every deviation from the paper and justify it.

That prompt forces it to either reveal a faithful implementation or expose where it improvised.

The cleanest way to use these is to ask the agent for a **paper-to-code mapping table** with columns:
**paper concept / equation / code file / function / tensor shape / verified?**

That usually surfaces mistakes immediately.

